## Why Centinela

Small services often fail quietly. A health endpoint starts timing out, a personal API goes down, or a dependency becomes flaky, and you only notice after checking manually.

Centinela is designed to answer the questions that matter first:

| Question | Centinela's role |
|---|---|
| Is this service up right now? | Run scheduled health checks and store the latest state. |
| How has it behaved over time? | Keep check history with status, latency, timestamps, and HTTP response data. |
| What happened when it failed? | Generate a readable incident summary with a local LLM in a later phase. |

The goal is not another giant observability platform. It is a focused, portfolio-grade monitoring system that demonstrates backend engineering, DevOps, observability, and local AI integration in one coherent project.

## What It Will Do

| Capability | Phase | Status |
|---|---:|---|
| Register services and endpoints to monitor | 1 | Planned |
| Run periodic HTTP health checks | 1 | Planned |
| Persist service and check history in PostgreSQL | 1 | Planned |
| Expose service-management and history APIs | 1 | Planned |
| Export Prometheus metrics | 2 | Planned |
| Visualize service health in Grafana | 2 | Planned |
| Detect incidents after repeated failures | 3 | Planned |
| Generate local AI incident summaries with Ollama | 3 | Planned |
| Deploy the full stack to local Kubernetes | 4 | Planned |
| Add automated validation with GitHub Actions | 5 | Planned |

## Project Status

> **Phase 0 is complete. Phase 1 is next.**

Planning, architecture, roadmap, and AI-agent context are in place. There is no runnable application code yet.

The next milestone is the basic backend:

- FastAPI project structure.
- PostgreSQL persistence.
- Service registration endpoints.
- Periodic health checks with APScheduler.
- Docker Compose for local execution.
- Basic tests.

See [`docs/ROADMAP.md`](./docs/ROADMAP.md) for the full phased plan.

## Planned User Flow

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    A[Register a service URL] --> B[Centinela checks it periodically]
    B --> C[Each check is stored in PostgreSQL]
    C --> D[Query health history through the API]
    D --> E[View metrics and dashboards]
    D --> F[Read AI incident summaries]
```

Target API shape:

```bash
# Register a service
curl -X POST http://localhost:8000/services \
  -H "X-API-Key: change-me" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"name": "Personal API", "url": "https://example.com/health", "check_interval_seconds": 60}'

# Read recent health history
curl http://localhost:8000/services/1/checks
```

These commands document the intended interface. They are not runnable until Phase 1 is implemented.

## Architecture

Phase 1 starts deliberately small: one FastAPI backend, PostgreSQL, and an in-process scheduler. Later phases add Prometheus, Grafana, Ollama, Kubernetes, and CI.

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    User((User)) --> API[FastAPI backend]
    API --> DB[(PostgreSQL)]
    API --> Scheduler[APScheduler]
    Scheduler --> Services[Monitored services]
    Scheduler --> DB
    API -. Phase 2 .-> Prometheus[Prometheus]
    Prometheus -. Phase 2 .-> Grafana[Grafana]
    Scheduler -. Phase 3 .-> Ollama[Ollama local LLM]
```

Read [`docs/ARCHITECTURE.md`](./docs/ARCHITECTURE.md) for the system design and decision context.

## Tech Stack

| Area | Choice |
|---|---|
| API | Python 3.11+ and FastAPI |
| Database | PostgreSQL |
| ORM and migrations | SQLAlchemy and Alembic |
| Validation | Pydantic |
| Scheduling | APScheduler |
| Metrics | Prometheus |
| Dashboards | Grafana |
| Local AI | Ollama |
| Containers | Docker and Docker Compose |
| Orchestration | Minikube or Kind |
| CI | GitHub Actions |

## How to Use This Repo Today

Until Phase 1 lands, this repository is best read as a project blueprint:

1. Start here for the product idea and planned user experience.
2. Read [`docs/ROADMAP.md`](./docs/ROADMAP.md) for the delivery sequence.
3. Read [`docs/ARCHITECTURE.md`](./docs/ARCHITECTURE.md) for the system design.
4. Read [`docs/DECISIONS_LOG.md`](./docs/DECISIONS_LOG.md) for the reasoning behind major choices.

When the backend exists, this section will become a real quick start with setup, run, and test commands.

